<font color="#FF0000">WE'RE ALL BEOUKU DINKY DOU</font><br>
<tt>Thu Sep 18  0:14:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Thank You Chet, Art and SW<br><br>
I've never believed myself to have PTSD, always been active, never never idle. I'm always creating; pictures, poems, writing, painting, and gardening no idle moments. I love to be alone, always handling three, four major issues at a time. Been involved in up to 20-30 social and political groups and functions at the same time until I retired from the Police force. Have over 1,500 books in my library, have what I believe a personal relationship with God from which I have gained much peace.<br>
Things really have never bothered me much, what others think about me. When they've gotten in my face I've shrug them off. Knowing what I could do, if I didn't control myself has always been there as a backup. So, I know I didn't need to prove anything to anyone.  <br>
Nothing on this site has ever gotten to me, I've really found the posting of certain individuals amusing and silly, nothing more. Like to toy with individuals like that always have. Did it with gang members, and individuals in high political positions in the government. Don't know if I've done it for their good or because I found it amusing. <br>
Have always found myself in the middle of major public issues but then I've always gone into the heat of battle, fights and hot shots when on the force. Have always had a lot of confidence and never scared or fearful. Love my kids, family, have a great family life, good wife. Never shared with her about Nam until I started writing the book. Didn't think much about Nam until about a year and a half ago. <br>
But, something has happened here, when I started writing to all of you. Dreams started thoughts and flashbacks about Vietnam but they made sense since they were issues currently on my mind, especially since editing the book. But even then it has not been negative. <br>
Couldn't read Ed's poems at first, too real, I read them quick without thinking of what they said, because they brought back the pain and sorrow but I also wanted to read them because of that and the memories of familiar things. When I finished writing my book before beginning the editing process I read the last page to my wife and broke down and cried. It was the first time ever.<br>
Never even cried when my mother, brother, and sister died. Have felt more pain for strangers then those of my immediate family.  Got a call today from my sister, her husband died this morning. No real feelings of lost, knew him to be a good men, good Christian he thought me a lot about the bible, feel an obligation to his flock more then to my sister. <br>
Since coming here I've had dreams of Marines I served with in Nam. Those I'm still looking for, nothing negative, before that I've had dreams of not being able to fire my police weapon in a confrontation situation because it had too long of a trigger pull, that's about the most negative dreams that I can recall. Still have them very once in a while. <br><br>
I've gone through a lot, but learned to just go around obstacles and go on with life. Little things don't bother me but hate injustice always wanting to correct what is wrong with the world, always taking on the bad guys. Have spent a lot of time counseling depressed and individuals with drinking and martial problems and have never been afraid to open up and share with others, if it would help them, that has brought me much peace. <br>
I hold back a lot, many have known me for years and never knew I was a police officer or that I served in Nam. I love to read, always reading but never fiction, I find that a waste of time. Don't really know if all of this is related to PTSD, Vietnam or just my character, but what you guys have posted there seems to point toward some association.<br>
Oh Well, maybe I should start another thread or write to the Marine Corps commandant and tell him to nail that Marine that fled to Canada instead of going to Nam. That doesn't really bother me, but I feel he did a lot a people (other Marines, and our country) wrong, it was just not right, can't see him getting off too easy. Justice would be mocked, see what I mean? <br><br>
Heck with it, maybe I'll just stir spatz up and then not answer him for a week.<br>
SW your post, same same me, me thinks were all beouku dinky dou.<br>

